node.text:
Wow!! 😮 Check out this rare footage of a glass octopus 🦑 
​
​With incredible powers of transparency only it's eyes, optic nerve and digestive tract remain opaque. This cephalopod, Vitreledonella richardi, was spotted near the remote Phoenix islands. Learn more about it through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷 Schmidt Ocean Institute

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 19, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Our eyes into the far reaches of the universe, the Hubble telescope that has captured many of the stunning space images we share here, has been offline since June 13. NASA finally repaired it with a 'risky' maneuver - read how through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
Pictured here are astronauts Jeffrey A. Hoffman and F. Story Musgrave, performing upgrades on the telescope in space back in 1993.
​
​📷 NASA/JSC

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 18, 2021. node.text:
Awww, how adorable! 😍 What are your faves?
​
​📷 WFKARS/Twitter

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 17, 2021. May be art.

node.text:
It's space, but really close together! 
​
​Just look at this utterly dazzling compilation of nebulas, supernovas and stars! 😍 This incredible image really brings home the spectacularly diverse array of these space phenomena - all essentially puffs of gas (some on fire!) gleaming like jewels against the dark depths of space.
​
​📷 @Cora.A.Harris/Instagram/NASA/ESA

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text:
What a blooming weirdo! 👽🌸😍 
​
​This enchantingly strange fairy lantern was discovered growing within the shadowy depths of a Malaysian rainforest. Lacking the sun-eating green chlorophyll and associated light capturing leaves, these plants are parasitic siphoning food through their roots from the fungal network shared by other rainforest plants.
​
​You can read more about this newly described species Thismia sitimeriamiae, through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷  University of Oxford

😍 With a massive wingspan of up to 30 cm (the size of ruler!!) this stunningly winged beauty is the largest butterfly species in the world. 🐛 🦋
​​
​Queen Alexandra's Birdwings (Ornithoptera alexandrae) adorn the forests of eastern Papua New Guinea, laying their eggs exclusively on a single species of pipevine plant. This one is a male - the females are the larger ones, colored black with brown.
​
​​Sadly, this fluttering giant is one of the many endangered animals threatened by habitat destruction for palm plantations. It is also highly prized in smuggling markets. 
​
​📷 @natural_history_museum

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 14, 2021. May be a closeup.

node.text:
Check out these insane snail licky-bits! 😱
​
​Snails use their weird as heck toothed-tongues - called radula - to grind all sorts of food. These 'teeth' are often softer than the surfaces where their foods are found, so they wear out quickly. So snails grow several new rows of 'teeth' each day.
​
The radula in this SEM micrograph belongs to a Spekia zonata, a species of freshwater snail from Lake Tanganyika in Africa.
​
​📷 Stanislav N. Gorb/Kiel University

😄 ​We humans see faces everywhere we look - from clouds to plug sockets. 
​
​This phenomenon is called face pareidolia. Researchers think its a kind of safety mechanism and a new study (which you can find through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert ) explains why. 
​
​📷 Taubert et al, Proceedings of the Royal Society B 2021

node.text:
Ever seen ice bend before?! 🧠💥
​
​Scientists have just grown microfibers of water ice at super low temperatures that can bend in a loop. This experiment has absolutely broken the previous record and is opening up new opportunities for the exploration of ice physics. 
​
​Read more at the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert
​
​📷: Peizhen Xu, Bowen Cui, Xin Guo, Limin Tong/Zhejiang University

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 11, 2021. May be an image of crustacean.

node.text:
Incredibly, this is glass not a hermit crab. A magnificent representation of the hundreds of species of hermit crabs that call our shores their home, this sculpture is 6 inches tall. Real hermit crabs range from a fraction of an inch long to nearly the size of a coconut.
​
🖌️ ​Tim Jerman/@Smithsonian/@americanart

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 10, 2021. May be an image of sky and text.

node.text:
This incredible photo is 100% real. 
​
​Taken all the way back in 1984, it shows Bruce McCandless II, a mission specialist on the Challenger spacecraft as he reached a maximum distance on one of the first untethered spacewalks ever. 
​
​After this picture was taken, he successfully used his 'jetpack' to come back to the Challenger with the rest of the crew. He reportedly said "may well have been one small step for Neil but it's a heck of a big leap for me!" 
​
​📷: NASA

This colorful array of growth is a Talaromyces species of mold, many of which are found naturally in soil. They ooze large amounts of red pigmented goo, which have captured the interest of food scientists as a food dye. Some species of this genus were originally classified under Penicillium - the genus within which we found antibiotics - and also produce antibiotic compounds themselves.
​
​📷 @fungitale
